  "prompt": "How is European hair different from African hair?",
  "response": "European hair and African hair exhibit several distinct differences primarily due to genetic and evolutionary factors. The key differences include:\n\n1. **Texture:** \n   - **European Hair:** Typically ranges from straight to wavy. European hair tends to have a more uniform texture and is generally smoother to touch.\n   - **African Hair:** Often characterized by its tightly coiled or kinky texture. African hair is usually thicker and has a more irregular, zigzag pattern. \n\n2. **Diameter:** \n   - **European Hair:** Generally finer and has a smaller diameter.\n   - **African Hair:** Typically coarser with a larger diameter.\n\n3. **Growth Rate:**\n   - **European Hair:** Tends to grow faster, at an average rate of approximately 1.2 centimeters (0.5 inches) per month.\n   - **African Hair:** Grows more slowly, at an average rate of approximately 0.9 centimeters (0.35 inches) per month.\n\n4. **Porosity:**\n   - Both hair types can vary in porosity, but African hair often tends to be more porous due to its curvature, making it more susceptible to dryness and breakage.\n\n5. **Cross-Section Shape:**\n   - **European Hair:** Generally oval or round in cross-section.\n   - **African Hair:** Typically elliptical or flat in cross-section, contributing to its curly or coiled nature.\n\n6. **Density:**\n   - **European Hair:** Traditionally, individuals with European heritage might have higher hair density, meaning the number of hairs per square centimeter.\n   - **African Hair:** May have lower density but due to the curliness, it appears fuller and more voluminous.\n\n7. **Fragility:**\n   - **European Hair:** Less prone to breakage and can retain moisture more effectively.\n   - **African Hair:** More prone to breakage and requires diligent moisturizing and care to prevent dryness.\n\nUnderstanding these differences is essential for appropriate hair care and styling practices tailored to each hair type.",
